`` Sonogenetics '' or control of brain cells by sound waves
this video shows how sound impulses influence the direction the patrols are moving .
scientists have raised worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves .
tiny patrols change direction by the time they are hit by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear .
the pulses work by switching the cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasonic waves .
related : scientists can read and write brain activity by light
the scientists said these worms are a great demonstration of a new methodology called sonogenetics , which uses ultrasound to activate brain , heart and muscle cells and activates outside the body .
Sreekanth Chalasani , a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla in California , said for the Guardian that this method could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrodes that stimulate the brain are implanted in the brain . the method is used , for example , to treat the symptoms of Parkinson 's disease .
polishes usually do not respond to ultrasound , but Chalasani found that the reaction occurs when placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles .
as he discovered , bubbles amplify ultrasonic waves that then pass through the body of worms .
enhanced ultrasonic waves operate in the ion channel TRP-4 , which is located in the membranes of some worm cells .
thanks to the sound waves , these channels are opening up and activating the cells they are associated with , the report says in the journal Nature Communications .
to control the tubers using ultrasonic waves , Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contain the ion channels of TRP-4 .
when then used on such modified worms , the sound waves were amplified by microbubbles and carried to worms , where modified motor neurons were switched on .
the new method is akin to optogenetics , a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn on and switch neurons through the light .
but Chalasani said that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique .
unlike the light , which must be sprinkled with optical fibre to the required site in the brain , ultrasonic waves can penetrate the tissues without restriction and be sent directly to the brain .
`` We believe that when we use gene therapy and therapeutic viruses , we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases , '' Chalasani said .
he added that the method would also be found in the treatment of muscle cells and insulin-producing cells .
